<subSubSection pageId="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,917,1953]" pageId="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,953,980]" pageId="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Verrucids with shell form depressed; apices of rostrum and carina marginal; operculum parallel to base (
<bibRefCitation author="Buckeridge, J. S." box="[216,477,990,1016]" pageId="3" pagination="125 - 149" refId="ref10188" refString="Buckeridge, J. S. (1997) Cirripedia: Thoracica. New ranges and species of Verrucomorpha from the Indian and Southwest Pacific Oceans. In: Crosnier, A. (Ed.), R e sultats des Campagnes MUSORSTOM. Vol. 18. M e moires du Mus e um national d'Histoire naturelle, 176, 125 - 149." type="journal article" year="1997">Buckeridge, 1997: 128</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,917,1953]" pageId="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1025,1052]" pageId="3">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schumacher" authorityYear="1817" box="[341,430,1027,1052]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[341,430,1027,1052]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as presently defined (
<bibRefCitation author="Buckeridge, J. S." box="[689,896,1026,1052]" pageId="3" pagination="125 - 149" refId="ref10188" refString="Buckeridge, J. S. (1997) Cirripedia: Thoracica. New ranges and species of Verrucomorpha from the Indian and Southwest Pacific Oceans. In: Crosnier, A. (Ed.), R e sultats des Campagnes MUSORSTOM. Vol. 18. M e moires du Mus e um national d'Histoire naturelle, 176, 125 - 149." type="journal article" year="1997">Buckeridge, 1997</bibRefCitation>
), is a convenience group comprising those verrucids with the operculum nearly parallel to the base, and marginal apices on the rostrum and the carina. Former subgenera of 
<emphasis box="[300,506,1098,1124]" italics="true" pageId="3">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schumacher" authorityYear="1817" box="[300,389,1099,1124]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="lato">Verruca</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[394,506,1098,1124]" pageId="3" sensu="lato">sensu lato</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
were elevated to full generic rank by 
<bibRefCitation author="Zevina, G. B." box="[921,1085,1098,1124]" pageId="3" pagination="1304 - 1313" refId="ref13962" refString="Zevina, G. B. (1987 a) Abyssal Cirripedia Verrucomorpha (Thoracica) of the Atlantic and Indian Ocean. Zoologicheskiy Zhurnal, 66 (9), 1304 - 1313. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1987">Zevina (1987a</bibRefCitation>
, b). This classification has been accepted by later workers. 
<bibRefCitation author="Young, P. S." box="[450,605,1134,1161]" pageId="3" pagination="31 - 92" refId="ref13923" refString="Young, P. S. (1998) Cirripedia (Crustacea) from the &quot; Campagne Biacores &quot; in the Azores region, including a generic revision of Verrucidae. Zoosystema, 20, 31 - 92." type="journal article" year="1998">Young (1998)</bibRefCitation>
named three more genera based on shell characters. Species of this genus, as presently restricted, fall into several lineages, which eventually may be separated into other genera (
<bibRefCitation author="Buckeridge, J. S." pageId="3" pagination="125 - 149" refId="ref10188" refString="Buckeridge, J. S. (1997) Cirripedia: Thoracica. New ranges and species of Verrucomorpha from the Indian and Southwest Pacific Oceans. In: Crosnier, A. (Ed.), R e sultats des Campagnes MUSORSTOM. Vol. 18. M e moires du Mus e um national d'Histoire naturelle, 176, 125 - 149." type="journal article" year="1997">Buckeridge, 1997</bibRefCitation>
). The lineage that includes depressed shells, such as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="O. F. Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[793,985,1207,1232]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stroemia">
<emphasis box="[793,985,1207,1232]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca stroemia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(typical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schumacher" authorityYear="1817" box="[1083,1172,1207,1232]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1083,1172,1207,1232]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), extends from the Late Cretaceous (late Maastrichtian; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gale, A. S." box="[509,634,1242,1268]" pageId="3" pagination="753 - 789" refId="ref11033" refString="Gale, A. S. (2014) Origin and phylogeny of verrucomorph barnacles (Crustacea, Cirripedia, Thoracica). Journal of Systematic Palaeontology, 13 (9), 753 - 789. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 14772019.2014.954409" type="journal article" year="2014">Gale, 2014</bibRefCitation>
) through the Recent, and comprises predominantly littoral species. The earliest records of this lineage occur in the Cretaceous of 
<collectingRegion box="[819,1021,1278,1305]" country="Australia" name="Western Australia" pageId="3">Western Australia</collectingRegion>
with 
<taxonomicName authority="tasmanica Buckeridge, 1983" authorityName="tasmanica Buckeridge" authorityYear="1983" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="tasmanica" subSpecies="tasmanica">
<emphasis box="[1089,1358,1279,1304]" italics="true" pageId="3">V. tasmanica tasmanica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Buckeridge, J. S." pageId="3" pagination="1 - 151" refId="ref10049" refString="Buckeridge, J. S. (1983) Fossil barnacles (Cirripedia: Thoracica) of New Zealand and Australia. New Zealand Geology Survey Paleontological Bulletin, 50, 1 - 151." type="journal article" year="1983">Buckeridge, 1983</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and now includes the taxa described in this paper. All of the species in this lineage have a fixed scutum with a well-formed adductor plate. In some species, such as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="O. F. Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[829,1022,1351,1376]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stroemia">
<emphasis box="[829,1022,1351,1376]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca stroemia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Buckeridge, 1997" authorityName="Buckeridge" authorityYear="1997" box="[1036,1389,1350,1376]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jago">
<emphasis box="[1036,1182,1351,1376]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca jago</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Buckeridge, J. S." box="[1189,1389,1350,1376]" pageId="3" pagination="125 - 149" refId="ref10188" refString="Buckeridge, J. S. (1997) Cirripedia: Thoracica. New ranges and species of Verrucomorpha from the Indian and Southwest Pacific Oceans. In: Crosnier, A. (Ed.), R e sultats des Campagnes MUSORSTOM. Vol. 18. M e moires du Mus e um national d'Histoire naturelle, 176, 125 - 149." type="journal article" year="1997">Buckeridge, 1997</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Foster &amp; Buckeridge, 1995" authorityName="Foster &amp; Buckeridge" authorityYear="1995" box="[151,650,1385,1413]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reunioni">
<emphasis box="[151,340,1387,1412]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca reunioni</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Foster, B. A. &amp; Buckeridge, J. S." box="[345,650,1385,1413]" pageId="3" pagination="345 - 382" refId="ref10969" refString="Foster, B. A. &amp; Buckeridge, J. S. (1995) Barnacles (Cirripedia: Thoracica) of Seas of Reunion Island and the East Indies. M emoires du Mus e um national d'Histoire naturelle, 16, A (4), 16 (2 - 4), 345 - 382. [for 1994]" type="journal article" year="1995">Foster &amp; Buckeridge, 1995</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, this plate extends to produce a rounded myophore. However, although all of the new species described herein possess a clear adductor plate, none have a definitive myophore.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,917,1953]" pageId="3">
<bibRefCitation author="Buckeridge, J. S." box="[199,467,1458,1484]" pageId="3" pagination="125 - 149" refId="ref10188" refString="Buckeridge, J. S. (1997) Cirripedia: Thoracica. New ranges and species of Verrucomorpha from the Indian and Southwest Pacific Oceans. In: Crosnier, A. (Ed.), R e sultats des Campagnes MUSORSTOM. Vol. 18. M e moires du Mus e um national d'Histoire naturelle, 176, 125 - 149." type="journal article" year="1997">Buckeridge (1997: 130)</bibRefCitation>
noted that fine, regularly spaced punctae extending from the exterior through the wall plates and opercula to the interior surface also characterize some members of this lineage. In extant species, such as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="O. F. Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[151,343,1531,1556]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stroemia">
<emphasis box="[151,343,1531,1556]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca stroemia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="G. B. Sowerby, 1827" authorityName="G. B. Sowerby" authorityYear="1827" box="[356,788,1530,1556]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevigata">
<emphasis box="[356,555,1530,1556]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca laevigata</emphasis>
G.B. 
<bibRefCitation author="Sowerby, G. B." box="[621,788,1530,1556]" pageId="3" refId="ref12993" refString="Sowerby, G. B. (1827) Genera of Recent and Fossil Shells. G. B. Sowerby, London. [unpaginated]" type="book" year="1827">Sowerby, 1827</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buckeridge" authorityYear="1997" box="[841,985,1531,1556]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jago">
<emphasis box="[841,985,1531,1556]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca jago</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, these punctae contain chitin, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Buckeridge, J. S." pageId="3" pagination="125 - 149" refId="ref10188" refString="Buckeridge, J. S. (1997) Cirripedia: Thoracica. New ranges and species of Verrucomorpha from the Indian and Southwest Pacific Oceans. In: Crosnier, A. (Ed.), R e sultats des Campagnes MUSORSTOM. Vol. 18. M e moires du Mus e um national d'Histoire naturelle, 176, 125 - 149." type="journal article" year="1997">Buckeridge (1997)</bibRefCitation>
considered it likely that this would have mitigated shell loss. In shallow, aerated coastal waters, where localized conditions could approach a pH of less than 7, this would have been advantageous in helping to preserve shell integrity. Punctae have also been observed in some fossil verrucids, e.g. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buckeridge" authorityYear="1983" box="[1032,1244,1639,1664]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tasmanica">
<emphasis box="[1032,1244,1639,1664]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca tasmanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Buckeridge in Buckeridge &amp; Finger, 2001" authorityName="Buckeridge in Buckeridge &amp; Finger" authorityYear="2001" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="digitali">
<emphasis box="[1259,1436,1638,1664]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca digitali</emphasis>
Buckeridge in 
<bibRefCitation author="Buckeridge, J. S. &amp; Finger, K. L." box="[314,617,1674,1700]" pageId="3" pagination="443 - 449" refId="ref10308" refString="Buckeridge, J. S. &amp; Finger, K. L. (2001) First record of a fossil verrucid barnacle in California, Verruca digitali sp. nov. (Cirripedia: Thoracica) from the late Miocene. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 21 (2), 443 - 449. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 20021975 - 99990145" type="journal article" year="2001">Buckeridge &amp; Finger, 2001</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(Miocene, California) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Buckeridge, in Buckeridge, Lee &amp; Robinson, 2014" authorityName="Buckeridge, in Buckeridge, Lee &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="2014" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viteus">
<emphasis box="[917,1077,1675,1700]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca viteus</emphasis>
Buckeridge, in 
<bibRefCitation author="Buckeridge, J. S. &amp; Lee, D. E. &amp; Robinson, J. H." pageId="3" pagination="253 - 263" refId="ref10450" refString="Buckeridge, J. S., Lee, D. E. &amp; Robinson, J. H. (2014) A diverse shallow water barnacle fauna assemblage (Cirripedia: Thoracica) from the Oligocene of New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Geology and Geophysics, 57 (1), 253 - 263. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00288306.2013.873472" type="journal article" year="2014">Buckeridge, Lee &amp; Robinson, 2014</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(Oligocene, 
<collectingCountry box="[500,654,1710,1737]" name="New Zealand" pageId="3">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
). Although they have not been recorded from 
<taxonomicName authority="Perreault &amp; Buckeridge, 2019" authorityName="Perreault &amp; Buckeridge" authorityYear="2019" box="[1163,1398,1710,1736]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alabamensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1163,1398,1710,1736]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca alabamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="3" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(this paper), 
<taxonomicName authority="Steinmann, 1921" authorityName="Steinmann in Wilkins" authorityYear="1921" box="[351,658,1746,1772]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rocana">
<emphasis box="[351,458,1747,1772]" italics="true" pageId="3">V. rocana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Steinmann, G." box="[467,658,1746,1772]" pageId="3" pagination="4 - 5" refId="ref13328" refString="Steinmann, G. (1921) Anhang. Uber eine Verruca von Roca. In: Wilckens, O. (Ed.), Beitr a ge zur Pal a ontologie von Patagonien, mit einem Beitrag von G. Steinmann. Neues Jahrbuch f u r Mineralogie, Geologie und Pal a ontologie, 1, pp. 4 - 5. [in German]" type="journal article" year="1921">Steinmann, 1921</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(Palaeocene, 
<collectingCountry box="[815,928,1746,1773]" name="Argentina" pageId="3">Argentina</collectingCountry>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Buckeridge, 2011" authorityName="Buckeridge" authorityYear="2011" box="[993,1369,1746,1772]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sauria">
<emphasis box="[993,1162,1747,1772]" italics="true" pageId="3">Verruca sauria</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Buckeridge, J. S." box="[1170,1369,1746,1772]" pageId="3" pagination="365 - 372" refId="ref10254" refString="Buckeridge, J. S. (2011) Taphonomy and systematics of a new Late Cretaceous verrucid barnacle (Cirripedia, Thoracica) from Canterbury, New Zealand. Palaeontology, 53, 365 - 372. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1475 - 4983.2010.00998. x" type="journal article" year="2011">Buckeridge, 2011</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(Late Cretaceous, 
<collectingCountry box="[290,445,1782,1809]" name="New Zealand" pageId="3">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
), their apparent absence may be due to diagenetic processes in some cases. They are apparently absent in 
<taxonomicName authority="Perreault &amp; Buckeridge, 2019" authorityName="Perreault &amp; Buckeridge" authorityYear="2019" box="[361,529,1818,1844]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alabamensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[361,529,1818,1844]" italics="true" pageId="3">V. alabamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[537,628,1819,1845]" pageId="3" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, and as the specimens are well preserved, punctae probably did not develop in this taxon. Nonetheless, the presence of punctae is a useful diagnostic feature for members of this lineage.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,917,1953]" pageId="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,346,1889,1916]" pageId="3">Occurrence.</emphasis>
Upper Cretaceous to Recent, cosmopolitan. Most known fossil species are shallow water. Living species may be found from the intertidal zone to 
<quantity box="[699,770,1926,1953]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.2" pageId="3" unit="m" value="620.0">620 m</quantity>
depth.
</paragraph>
